We have to look at the probability of not getting the bounty (97%). The probability of something not occurring in n tries is the probability of it not occurring in 1 try to the n^th power. If we repeat the task ten times, then the probability of not getting the bounty goes to (97%)^10 = .97^10 = .737 = 73.7% So if we subtract 100%-73.7%, then the probability of getting the bounty at least once in 10 tries is 26.3%.

Internet (IP) addresses are allocated in blocks. Any address is a 32 bit number, which means it is composed of 32 binary digits. When a block is allocated the first bits (digits) are assigned and this defines the block. In other words addresses within the block all share the same leading digits. In this case the bottom 10 bits were left unassigned, leaving 2^10 = 1024 possible addresses. This is the same as stating that 3 decimal digits have a 10^3 = 1000 combinations. Edit: formatting

So what you're looking for is a way of "classifying" songs as "I will like this" or "I won't like this". Alternatively you're looking at the "regression" problem which tries to answer "I will like this song this amount". I think the easiest framework to view the problem with is: given this set of song features (X) predict whether I'll like the song or not (Y). Here lies your biggest challenge: turning your song into something where you're likely to actually get good classification results with only a 100 songs. Spotify has a huge advantage: the don't need to classify songs based on what they sound like. The features they use (I believe) are the other songs that people often listen to with any given song. And they have an enormous dataset. Pandora solves this problem by having people listing to songs and manually recording a massive number of features from the song (Pandora calls them genes). What you're looking to do is come up with these features automatically. There are two approaches here: Manual feature selection. This is the more traditional ML approach. You'd ask an algorithm to select easily computable properties of each song like BPM, average pitch, and whatnot and do it's classification on these properties. The problem is that what makes us "like" or "dislike" a song might not be encoded in these features. You can also have the algorithm come up with the features for you. This is the central idea in deep learning. This might look like feeding the song into your algorithm raw, or with more restricted preprocessing where it still roughly looks like a song. As a first guess, I'd try using FFT to produce a spectrogram of the song and feeding short clips into a couple layers of 1D convolutions. The problem is that for the CNN for find useful features of your songs it will need lots of data. You might be able to work around this by using a semi-supervised approach. Maybe you can train a network to classify whether two clips come from the same song, then use the learned features to determine if you'll like the song. Hopefully this at least starts you out on the right things to google.
